"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678586","Department for Education","false","2017-02-10","<p>The following table shows the time series of average salaries for full-time teaching assistants in all state funded schools in England. Figures for 2010 are not available.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>All Full-time Teaching Assistants</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2011</strong></p></td><td><p>£18,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2012</strong></p></td><td><p>£18,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2013</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2014</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,000</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>2015</strong></p></td><td><p>£19,200</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: School Workforce Census</p><p>Salaries are rounded to the nearest £100.</p><p> </p><p>These figures are consistent with those published in PQ60334 published in Hansard, which is available at the following web link: <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-01-17/60334" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2017-01-17/60334</a></p><p>The figures published in the answer of 10 June 2015 to Question 856 included both full and part-time teaching assistants. The preference is to show salaries for full-time teaching assistants because the salary data for part-time teaching assistants is not always provided on a comparable basis.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-10T21:18:01.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678586/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678586/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678586/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Schools: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 20 January 2017 to Question 60334, and with reference to the Answer of 10 June 2015 to Question 856, whether the figures supplied in those answers for the average salaries of teaching assistants in November 2013 and November 2015 were calculated on the same basis.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","61628"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678587","Department for Education","false","2017-02-01","<p>The number and characteristics of teaching assistants and school support staff employed in state-funded schools in England is published in the annual series of statistical first releases ‘School Workforce in England’. The latest available information, as at November 2015, is in tables 1, 2b, 3b and 6 at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/school-workforce-in-england-november-2015</a></p><p> </p><p>Information is not collected centrally for teaching assistants and school support staff on the following: recruitment and retention, performance and effectiveness, days lost due to sickness, skills attained, and term-time only contracts.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-01T16:40:49.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678587/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678587/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678587/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Schools: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what information her Department holds relating to teaching assistants and other school support staff on trends in (a) teacher recruitment and retention, (b) performance and effectiveness, (c) days lost due to sickness, (d) skills attained and (e) employment on term-time-only contracts.","false","Biography information for Lilian Greenwood","Nottingham South","Lilian Greenwood","61629"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678589","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>This data is not held centrally by the Department.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-30T11:36:57.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678589/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678589/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678589/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Breakfast Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of school-age children regularly attend a school breakfast club.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","61705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678590","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>This data can be found in the Childcare and Early Years Survey of Parents, which is published every two years. Data from the most recent survey, published in March 2016, for 2014 to 2015 shows use of childcare providers, including ‘after-school club or activity’, during their most recent term-time week by age of child (in Table 2.3 of the main report). This table and accompanying information can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-survey-of-parents-2014-to-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/childcare-and-early-years-survey-of-parents-2014-to-2015</a></p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-30T16:14:05.073Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678590/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678590/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678590/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","After School Clubs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what proportion of school-age children regularly attend an after-school club.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","61706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678591","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The information is not held in the format requested.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-30T16:32:32.457Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678591/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678591/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678591/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","GCE A-level","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many students achieved three or more A grade or higher A-levels in each ethnic group for each year since 2006.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","61549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678592","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government places a high priority on education, recognising its importance to productivity and social mobility. At the 2015 Spending Review the overall envelope for schools funding to 2019-20 was set, taking into account anticipated new costs on schools. At the Spending Review, the core schools budget[1] was protected in real terms - as a result, throughout this Parliament, the money available for our schools will increase as pupil numbers rise.</p><p> </p><p>The new, fairer National Funding Formula will ensure that the resources allocated at the Spending Review is distributed fairly, consistently and transparently across the country to match school and pupil need. This will end the current system where pupils and schools in identical circumstances attract differing funding levels due to where they live.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p>We are also committed to providing support for schools to make the most of their money. In January, we published a wide range of tools and support available at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/schools-financial-health-and-efficiency</a>, and we recently launched a school buying strategy to support schools to save over £1bn a year by 2019-20 on their non-staff spend.</p><p> </p><p>[1] https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/spending-review-and-autumn-statement-2015-documents</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-30T17:18:28.353Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678592/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678592/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678592/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Schools: Bristol West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 14 December 2016 to Question 56753, what mechanisms the national funding formula will use to account for the cost pressures which schools face.","false","Biography information for Thangam Debbonaire","Bristol West","Thangam Debbonaire","61540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678593","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Children and Young Persons Act 2008 (Relevant Care Functions) (England) Regulations 2014 are clear that local authorities may not contract out child protection functions to any organisation that is operated for profit. The Government has no intention of revisiting the settled position on this matter.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-30T16:22:51.727Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678593/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678593/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678593/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Children: Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will take steps to prohibit subsidiaries of profit-making companies from contracting with local authorities to run child protection and other children's social care services.","false","Biography information for Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","South Shields","Mrs Emma Lewell-Buck","61584"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678594","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government sets a clear statutory framework for safeguarding and child protection. The statutory framework makes it clear, that local authorities have overarching duties for safeguarding and promoting the welfare of individual children and young people in their area, established through the Children Act 1989.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically, section 17 of that Act requires local authorities to provide services to children in need in their area, no matter where they live or where they are educated. Section 47 of the same Act requires local authorities to investigate whether action should be taken by them to safeguard or promote the welfare of children suffering, or likely to suffer, significant harm.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory guidance, <em>Working Together to Safeguard Children </em>(2015), sets out how these duties should be complied with by local authorities. In addition, the Government has issued separate non-statutory advice for local authorities on elective home education, which contains guidance in relation to safeguarding.</p><p> </p><p>Local authority revenue expenditure on children’s social care is funded from the general local government settlement. Local authority expenditure on children’s services is around £7bn (safeguarding, adoption, looked after children, family services; of which £5.9bn is comprised of safeguarding, adoption and looked after children services).</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","61772 ; 61795","2017-01-30T15:47:09.657Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678594/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678594/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678594/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what funding is provided by her Department for safeguarding of students who are being educated at home.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","61794"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678595","Department for Education","false","2017-01-31","<p>We have confirmed a minimum of £440m funding available for non-levy paying employers for 2017-18 and we are committed to funding high quality apprenticeships over the Parliament. Decisions on future years’ funding will be made on the basis of ongoing monitoring of employer demand, performance and budgets.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-31T15:01:28.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678595/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678595/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678595/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, if she will guarantee apprenticeship funding for non-levy paying employers in (a) 2018-19, (b) 2019-20 and (c) 2020-21.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","61753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678596","Department for Education","false","2017-01-31","<p>Schools and colleges receive disadvantage funding as part of their general 16-19 funding to help them support disadvantaged young people. In 2016/17 this funding totalled just under £550 million. Disadvantage funding is not ring fenced. This means institutions are free to use this element of the funding to choose the best way to attract, retain and support disadvantaged students and those with learning difficulties and disabilities. Providers also receive a 16-19 bursary fund allocation to provide discretionary bursaries for financially disadvantaged young people who need additional support to help them with costs, such as transport. Schools and colleges were allocated £132 million of bursary funding in 2016/17. Additionally, students in defined vulnerable groups are eligible for yearly bursaries of £1,200 (pro-rata for part-timers).</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not collect detailed information on how the disadvantage funding and bursary fund allocation is used, nor does it dictate exactly how the money should be spent. Post-16 institutions have a good deal of flexibility in how they can use their overall resources to support students. Some colleges support bus transport. However, the Department does not collect data on the amount of money spent on this.</p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-31T14:59:15.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678596/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678596/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678596/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Further Education: Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the oral contribution of the Minister of State for Apprenticeships and Skills of 9 January 2017, Official Report, column 114, how much of the £550 million disadvantage funding for post-16 places will be spent on subsidising college buses in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Gordon Marsden","Blackpool South","Gordon Marsden","61752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678597","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government sets a clear statutory framework for safeguarding and child protection. The statutory framework makes it clear, that local authorities have overarching duties for safeguarding and promoting the welfare of individual children and young people in their area, established through the Children Act 1989.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically, section 17 of that Act requires local authorities to provide services to children in need in their area, no matter where they live or where they are educated. Section 47 of the same Act requires local authorities to investigate whether action should be taken by them to safeguard or promote the welfare of children suffering, or likely to suffer, significant harm.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory guidance, <em>Working Together to Safeguard Children </em>(2015), sets out how these duties should be complied with by local authorities. In addition, the Government has issued separate non-statutory advice for local authorities on elective home education, which contains guidance in relation to safeguarding.</p><p> </p><p>Local authority revenue expenditure on children’s social care is funded from the general local government settlement. Local authority expenditure on children’s services is around £7bn (safeguarding, adoption, looked after children, family services; of which £5.9bn is comprised of safeguarding, adoption and looked after children services).</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","61772 ; 61794","2017-01-30T15:47:09.763Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678597/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678597/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678597/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what steps her Department takes to ensure that children who are being educated at home are safeguarded.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","61795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678598","Department for Education","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government sets a clear statutory framework for safeguarding and child protection. The statutory framework makes it clear, that local authorities have overarching duties for safeguarding and promoting the welfare of individual children and young people in their area, established through the Children Act 1989.</p><p> </p><p>Specifically, section 17 of that Act requires local authorities to provide services to children in need in their area, no matter where they live or where they are educated. Section 47 of the same Act requires local authorities to investigate whether action should be taken by them to safeguard or promote the welfare of children suffering, or likely to suffer, significant harm.</p><p> </p><p>The statutory guidance, <em>Working Together to Safeguard Children </em>(2015), sets out how these duties should be complied with by local authorities. In addition, the Government has issued separate non-statutory advice for local authorities on elective home education, which contains guidance in relation to safeguarding.</p><p> </p><p>Local authority revenue expenditure on children’s social care is funded from the general local government settlement. Local authority expenditure on children’s services is around £7bn (safeguarding, adoption, looked after children, family services; of which £5.9bn is comprised of safeguarding, adoption and looked after children services).</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson","61794 ; 61795","2017-01-30T15:47:09.703Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678598/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678598/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678598/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-25","Home Education","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, what statutory guidance exists on protecting the welfare of students who are being educated at home.","false","Biography information for Royston Smith","Southampton, Itchen","Royston Smith","61772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678599","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-02","<p>The numbers of cases of avian influenza confirmed in domestic flocks in England and Wales, by year and month in the last 24 months up to and including 31/01/2017, are shown in the table below. In addition the numbers of positive cases found in wild birds in England and Wales are shown.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cases in Domestic Flocks</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cases in Wild Birds</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>August</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Government has taken swift action to limit the spread of avian influenza, with restrictions around affected premises and wider measures in place across the country. These measures included increasing the sensitivity of the surveillance that is undertaken around wetland areas by key partners due to the increased prevalence of H5N8 in Europe.</p><p> </p><p>To reduce the risk of bird flu spreading from bird to bird there is currently a requirement for all poultry keepers, even those who just keep a few birds as pets, to take all practicable and appropriate steps to keep their birds housed or otherwise separate from wild birds. There is also a ban on poultry gatherings.</p><p> </p><p>Bird flu is also transmitted via the environment, for example in wild bird droppings, and it is vital that keepers practice strict biosecurity.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-02T10:36:39.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678599/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678599/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678599/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Avian Influenza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, how many instances of avian flu were identified in sites in England and Wales in each of the last 24 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61743"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678600","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-31","<p>There are currently 16 wild animals licensed by Defra for use by travelling circuses in England. The 16 wild animals are 6 Reindeer; 3 Camels; 3 Zebra; 1 Fox; 1 Macaw; 1 Racoon and 1 Zebu.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-31T14:52:47.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678600/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678600/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678600/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Animal Welfare: Circuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, (a) how many wild animals and (b) of which species are licensed in circuses.","false","Biography information for Rachael Maskell","York Central","Rachael Maskell","61557"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678601","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-02-02","<p>The numbers of cases of avian influenza confirmed in domestic flocks in England and Wales, by year and month in the last 24 months up to and including 31/01/2017, are shown in the table below. In addition the numbers of positive cases found in wild birds in England and Wales are shown.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Month</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cases in Domestic Flocks</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Cases in Wild Birds</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>July</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>August</p></td><td><p> </p></td><td><p>1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2016</p></td><td><p>December</p></td><td><p>1</p></td><td><p>7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2017</p></td><td><p>January</p></td><td><p>7</p></td><td><p>10</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Government has taken swift action to limit the spread of avian influenza, with restrictions around affected premises and wider measures in place across the country. These measures included increasing the sensitivity of the surveillance that is undertaken around wetland areas by key partners due to the increased prevalence of H5N8 in Europe.</p><p> </p><p>To reduce the risk of bird flu spreading from bird to bird there is currently a requirement for all poultry keepers, even those who just keep a few birds as pets, to take all practicable and appropriate steps to keep their birds housed or otherwise separate from wild birds. There is also a ban on poultry gatherings.</p><p> </p><p>Bird flu is also transmitted via the environment, for example in wild bird droppings, and it is vital that keepers practice strict biosecurity.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-02-02T10:35:16.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678601/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678601/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678601/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Avian Influenza","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what information her Department holds of the number of instances of avian flu identified in sites across England and Wales in each of the last 24 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","61614"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678602","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-30","<p>Retaining market access between the UK and the EU will be a significant benefit to the food and farming sectors in both the UK and Europe. In 2015, the UK exported £11 billion of agri-food and drink products to the EU, and imported £28 billion. We aim to secure a mutually beneficial deal that delivers market access for the benefit of food and drink producers both in the UK and the EU.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-30T12:38:29.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678602/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678602/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678602/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what steps she plans to take to secure access to EU markets for (a) UK exports and (b) Scotch whisky in negotiations on the UK leaving the EU.","false","Biography information for Calum Kerr","Berwickshire, Roxburgh and Selkirk","Calum Kerr","61651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678603","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-30","<p>Local authorities do have a role to play in tackling fine particulate matter (PM<sub>2.5</sub>) and this was introduced through statutory guidance published last April. It requires local authorities to work towards reducing emissions and concentrations of PM<sub>2.5 </sub>in their local area alongside measures to tackle other pollutants.</p><p> </p><p>Local authorities do have powers available to them to help tackle key sources of PM such as those to establish Smoke Control Areas and on transport.</p><p> </p><p>The Public Health Outcomes Framework also includes an indicator based on PM<sub>2.5 </sub>impacts on mortality. This was introduced to support local authority public health professionals and air quality managers to appraise PM2.5 levels in their area.</p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-30T17:10:57.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678603/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678603/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678603/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, for what reason local authorities have no direct responsibility to control PM2.5 concentrations; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Andrew Selous","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","61707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678604","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Prime Minister announced last year our plans for a Repeal Bill that will convert current EU law into domestic British law. Our intention is to ensure a smooth and orderly transition via the Repeal Bill. Without pre-judging what our future relationship with the EU will be or future decisions Parliament may make, this will provide as much certainty as possible by maintaining the existing laws; and this will include laws transposing the EU Urban Waste Water Treatment Directive.</p><p> </p>","Suffolk Coastal","Dr Thérèse Coffey",,"2017-01-31T13:46:21.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678604/answer","Biography information for Dr Thérèse  Coffey","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678604/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678604/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Water Treatment: EU Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether it is her policy that the EU Urban Wastewater Treatment Directive will be incorporated in full into UK law when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Angela Smith","Penistone and Stocksbridge","Angela Smith","61729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678605","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2017-01-31","<p>There is no record of discussions with representatives of the agricultural or retail sectors to discuss the decline in oilseed rape harvests specifically. Defra continues to support the improvement of oilseed rape through its Oilseed Rape Genetic Improvement Network (OREGIN). This network is dedicated to the development of new pre-breeding material with key resilience traits such as resistance to fungal pathogens, improved nutrient uptake efficiency, rooting and establishment as well as improved quality traits</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2017-01-31T13:44:20.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678605/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678605/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678605/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2017-01-25","Oilseed Rape","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, on what dates she has met representatives of the (a) agricultural and (b) retail sectors to discuss the decline in oilseed rape harvests; and what steps she has taken as a result of those meetings.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678606","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>We welcome the progress that has occurred in Papua and West Papua under President Jokowi. However we remain concerned with the human rights situation in Papua, including most recently a number of incidents involving security forces in December 2016 which resulted in fatalities. We encourage the Indonesian Human Rights Commission to complete investigations into human rights cases in West Papua impartially and objectively.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:13:39.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678606/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678606/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678606/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Papua: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the human rights situation in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61742"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678607","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>Piracy remains a serious problem and the Government keeps threat levels under regular review. I chaired a Ministerial Working Group on Maritime Security on 3 November 2016, at which the range of threats to British maritime interests, including piracy was reviewed, and the work being done to protect our interests both at home and overseas.</p><p>The Government's assessment is that piracy is on the decline in the Straits of Malacca and Singapore Strait. It remains suppressed but not eliminated in the West Indian Ocean and Gulf of Aden, where there remains a threat emanating from Somalia. In the Gulf of Guinea, we are concerned by an apparent increase in the number of attacks and a trend towards kidnapping crew for ransom.</p><p>The UK continues to play a leading role in efforts to uphold global maritime security. We provide the Commander and Operational Headquarters for the EU's Operation Atalanta whose mission includes deterring and disrupting piracy in the Southern Red Sea, the Gulf of Aden and a large part of the Indian Ocean. We also help to safeguard shipping in those areas through the Royal Navy's United Kingdom Maritime Trade Operations (UKMTO). In June 2016 the Royal Navy and the French Marine Nationale established the 'Maritime Domain Awareness for Trade - Gulf of Guinea' reporting mechanism which enables information on maritime incidents to be shared with shipping in West Africa. We also support capacity building programmes in West and East Africa, and in South-East Asia.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-02-02T16:13:04.677Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678607/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678607/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678607/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Piracy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the level of threat from piracy in (a) current and (b) prospective shipping lanes of economic interest to the UK.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678608","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>Neither the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), nor his Ministerial team, have yet had an opportunity to discuss West Papua with their Indonesian counterparts. Our Ambassador to Indonesia visits Papua and West Papua annually, most recently in January 2016. During these visits, he meets key stakeholders in the regional government, police, universities and other officials and raises a range of issues with them regarding the situation in West Papua.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:08:23.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678608/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678608/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678608/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Papua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Indonesian counterpart on conflict in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61719"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678609","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The British Government supports the effort of those who are trying to address the problems of West Papua and enable it to enjoy the same level of peace, stability and prosperity as other parts of Indonesia. We also encourage meaningful dialogue between all parties and remain committed to urging all levels of government to work with Papuans towards solving their regional governance disputes peacefully.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:09:31.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678609/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678609/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678609/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Papua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps his Department is taking to promote peace in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61720"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678610","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>​Neither the Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), nor his Ministerial team, have discussed West Papua with their counterparts from Papua New Guinea.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:11:30.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678610/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678610/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678610/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Papua: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart from Papua New Guinea on conflict in West Papua.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678611","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>Foreign and Commonwealth Office ministers have no plans to visit Papua New Guinea in the near future. However, the UK values its relationship with Papua New Guinea and ministerial travel is constantly under review.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:10:27.123Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678611/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678611/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678611/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Papua New Guinea: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether (a) he and (b) the Minister for Asia and the Pacific plans to visit Papua New Guinea in the near future.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61721"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678612","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>We welcome the political deal signed on 31 December. As I said in my statement of 6 January, it is imperative that this deal is implemented as soon as possible so that elections can take place this year. We continue to encourage the Democratic Republic of the Congo government and the opposition to cooperate and consolidate the progress they have already made.</p><p>The UK has earmarked £11.4 million to support a transparent electoral process provided that a realistic budget and timetable are released, and all the conditions set out in the Constitution and in UN Security Council Resolution 2277 are met. If necessary we will push for EU sanctions to be imposed on those who obstruct the democratic process and commit human rights violations.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-01-30T16:35:43.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678612/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678612/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678612/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Democratic Republic of Congo: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what steps the Government is taking to ensure that President Kabila abides by the 31 December 2016 agreement reached in the Democratic Republic of Congo to ensure that free and fair elections take place in that country before the end of 2017.","false","Biography information for Liz McInnes","Heywood and Middleton","Liz McInnes","61662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678614","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>As is standard practice, Embassy staff in Belgrade worked with the Foreign and Commonwealth Office's Western Balkans Department, Media Office and the Foreign Secretary's Private Office on the visit. This included developing an itinerary, providing briefing and a media plan, making the necessary travel arrangements, as well as liaising with Serbian Government protocol and other local authorities.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-01-30T17:31:40.047Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678614/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678614/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678614/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Serbia: Visits Abroad","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Answer of 24 January 2017 to Question 60166, what preparations (a) his Department and (b) the British Embassy in Belgrade undertook prior to his official visit to Serbia in November 2016.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","61655"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678615","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Overseas Security and Justice Assistance assessment for the regional MSc in Security Sector Management identified no serious risk of it directly or significantly contributing to a violation of human rights.</p><p>The programme is itself designed to directly mitigate the risk of human rights abuses. Human rights features prominently as a cross-cutting theme throughout the course.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2017-02-01T14:23:21.417Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678615/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678615/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678615/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","Ethiopia: Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether his Department identified any human rights risks in the Overseas Security and Justice Assistance assessment it conducted for the regional MSc in Security Sector Management in Ethiopia.","false","Biography information for Chris Law","Dundee West","Chris Law","61665"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678617","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), raised the South China Sea with Chinese State Councillor Yang Jiechi during the UK-China Strategic Dialogue in London on 20 December. He noted the importance of abiding by international law in the South China Sea and refraining from activities which could raise tensions. As the Foreign Secretary has since stressed in a speech on 18 January, we oppose the militarisation of the South China Sea and we urge all parties to respect freedom of navigation and settle their disputes peacefully in accordance with international law. We regard last year's ruling by the Permanent Court of Arbitration in The Hague as binding on both China and the Philippines.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T15:04:38.867Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678617/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678617/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678617/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","South China Sea: Disputed Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his Chinese counterpart on building on disputed islands in the South China Sea.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61535"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678618","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), has not had discussions with his Philippine counterpart on building on disputed islands in the South China Sea. However, I discussed the situation in the South China Sea with Philippine interlocutors when I visited Manila in December, underlining the British Government's well known position. As the Foreign Secretary made clear in a speech on 18 January, we oppose the militarisation of the South China Sea and we urge all parties to respect freedom of navigation and settle their disputes peacefully in accordance with international law. We regard last year's ruling by the Permanent Court of Arbitration in The Hague as binding on both China and the Philippines.</p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T16:00:02.55Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678618/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678618/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678618/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","South China Sea: Disputed Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the Philippines on building on disputed islands in the South China Sea.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678619","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>We oppose the militarisation of the South China Sea and we urge all parties to respect freedom of navigation and settle their disputes peacefully in accordance with international law. We do not comment on the content of discussions between ministers and their officials. However, the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Boris Johnson), discusses the full range of issues related to the UN with our Permanent Representative to the UN.</p><p> </p>","Reading West","Alok Sharma",,"2017-02-02T16:02:29.407Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678619/answer","Biography information for Alok Sharma","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678619/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678619/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","South China Sea: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with the UK's Permanent Representative at the UN on the security situation in the South China Sea.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678620","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Foreign Secretary, my Rt Hon. Friend the Member for Uxbridge and South Ruislip (Mr Johnson), travelled to the US on 8-9 January where he held constructive discussions with the then President elect Trump’s closest advisers and with Congressional leaders. We look forward to building ties with the US to safeguard the security and prosperity of our nations in the years ahead. The Foreign Secretary will meet his counterparts at the earliest opportunity once the Secretary of State has been appointed.</p>","Rutland and Melton","Sir Alan Duncan",,"2017-02-02T16:16:09.247Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678620/answer","Biography information for Sir Alan Duncan","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678620/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678620/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2017-01-25","USA: Foreign Relations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, when he plans to visit the US; and when he plans to meet his US counterpart.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","61538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678621","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The UK National Screening Committee plans to review the evidence for atrial fibrillation in the financial year 2017/18 as part of its three yearly cycle. More information on the review and how to participate in the public consultation is available at:</p><p><a href="https://legacyscreening.phe.org.uk/atrialfibrillation" target="_blank">https://legacyscreening.phe.org.uk/atrialfibrillation</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T15:42:09.477Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678621/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678621/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678621/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Atrial Fibrillation: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the UK National Screening Committee plans to begin its review of systematic population screening for atrial fibrillation.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","61543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678622","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>According to our latest estimates, there are about 16,000 strokes as a consequence of atrial fibrillation (AF) per year in England. The average cost of stroke in the first year after onset is £13,459 in health costs and £8,716 in social care costs totalling £22,175. After five years the accumulated costs are £45,233. An AF related stroke is on average more severe than other strokes and the average five year costs are nearer £60,000.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T15:58:20.57Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678622/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678622/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678622/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Atrial Fibrillation: Strokes","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what the annual financial cost is of atrial fibrillation-related stroke to the NHS.","false","Biography information for Derek Twigg","Halton","Derek Twigg","61544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678623","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>Ministers welcome Cervical Cancer Prevention Week. We are fully supportive of the work Jo’s Cervical Cancer Trust does to raise awareness of cervical cancer and the importance of cervical screening for eligible women. We have provided a supportive quote to Jo's Cervical Cancer Trust and will be active on social media throughout this week.</p><p> </p><p>Human papillomavirus vaccine has been given to more than three million teenage girls across the United Kingdom since our vaccination programme started in 2008 and coverage is amongst the highest in the world. The number of young women with pre-cancerous lesions is falling and protection is expected to be long term helping to protect women against cervical cancer, eventually saving hundreds of lives each year.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T16:00:51.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678623/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678623/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678623/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Cervical Cancer","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps his Department took to support Cervical Cancer Prevention Week.","false","Biography information for Mr John Baron","Basildon and Billericay","Mr John Baron","61545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678624","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2017-01-30","<p>The specific information requested in part (a) is not readily available, and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p><p>Statistics on the number of Employment and Support Allowance claimants with a primary medical condition of ‘Diseases of the skin and subcutaneous system’ by Parliamentary Constituency can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/Default.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/Default.asp</a></p><p>Guidance for users is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp" target="_blank">https://www.nomisweb.co.uk/home/newuser.asp</a></p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2017-01-30T16:02:55.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678624/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678624/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678624/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2017-01-25","Skin Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in each parliamentary constituency who receive employment and support allowance have been diagnosed with (a) hidradenitis suppurativa and (b) a dermatological condition in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678625","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The attached table gives a count of finished admissions episodes with a primary diagnosis of hidradenitis suppurativa and dermatological conditions for the years 2011-12 to 2015-16 by parliamentary constituency.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T16:55:40.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678625/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678625/answer","PQ61547 attached document.xlsx","PQ61547 attached document.xlsx","PQ61547 attached document","PQ61547 attached document","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678625/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Skin Diseases","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many finished admission episodes there were in each parliamentary constituency where a patient was diagnosed as having (a) hidradenitis suppurativa and (b) a dermatological condition in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Rosie Cooper","West Lancashire","Rosie Cooper","61547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678626","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>The National Health Service is a national, not an international, service. This Government was the first to introduce tough measures to clamp down on migrants accessing free NHS care, including introducing the immigration health surcharge.</p><p> </p><p>The initiatives we have implemented have meant the income identified from visitors and migrants has trebled from £89 million in 2012/13 to £289 million in 2015/16.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2017-02-02T13:35:40.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678626/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678626/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678626/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Health Services: Foreign Nationals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent progress his Department has made on recovering money from overseas visitors and other chargeable NHS patients.","false","Biography information for Henry Smith","Crawley","Henry Smith","61532"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678627","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>The NHS Cervical Screening Programme is directly commissioned by NHS England as part of the Section 7A agreement of the National Health Service Act 2006, as amended by the Health and Social Care Act 2012. The availability of screening within contraception and sexual health clinics, which are commissioned by local authorities, is a matter for local agreement.</p><p> </p><p>There is also the human papillomavirus (HPV) adolescent vaccination programme for girls which is well established in the United Kingdom and expected to have a significant impact on reducing cervical cancer. Since the start of the programme in 2008, more than 8.5 million doses of the HPV vaccine have been given in the UK, with close to 90% of eligible teenagers vaccinated.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-02T16:52:52.673Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678627/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678627/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678627/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Cervical Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether cervical screening is available to all women at contraception and sexual health clinics.","false","Biography information for Mr John Baron","Basildon and Billericay","Mr John Baron","61533"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678629","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Section 35 of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 has never been used to withhold information in response to requests concerning valproate.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-02T17:45:32.77Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678629/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678629/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678629/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Pregnancy: Sodium Valproate","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, on how many occasions section 35 of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 has been applied to cases where Valporate has been prescribed to pregnant women.","false","Biography information for Cat Smith","Lancaster and Fleetwood","Cat Smith","61599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678630","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department, on behalf of the United Kingdom Government, reimburses other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing treatment to people we are responsible for under European Union law, irrespective of nationality. In the same way, other EEA countries and Switzerland reimburse the UK for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The requested data regarding individual trusts is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS trusts and foundation trusts publish data on amounts claimed for directly chargeable overseas patients in their annual accounts. This data does not include patients from the EEA and Switzerland whose treatment would be reimbursed under Regulations (EC) Nos 883/2004 and 987/2009. Data in trusts’ annual accounts includes:</p><p> </p><p>- Income recognised this year (invoiced amounts and accruals);</p><p>- Cash payments received in-year (invoices issued this year);</p><p>- Amounts added to provision for impairment of receivables (receivables at previous year end); and</p><p>- Amounts written off in-year (irrespective of year of recognition).</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","61601 ; 61607 ; 61639 ; 61640 ; 61641 ; 61645 ; 61646 ; 61782","2017-01-30T17:53:06.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678630/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678630/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678630/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Northern General Hospital","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was reclaimed in health costs from foreign governments in each of the last three years by Northern General Hospital.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","61606"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678631","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department, on behalf of the United Kingdom Government, reimburses other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing treatment to people we are responsible for under European Union law, irrespective of nationality. In the same way, other EEA countries and Switzerland reimburse the UK for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The requested data regarding individual trusts is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS trusts and foundation trusts publish data on amounts claimed for directly chargeable overseas patients in their annual accounts. This data does not include patients from the EEA and Switzerland whose treatment would be reimbursed under Regulations (EC) Nos 883/2004 and 987/2009. Data in trusts’ annual accounts includes:</p><p> </p><p>- Income recognised this year (invoiced amounts and accruals);</p><p>- Cash payments received in-year (invoices issued this year);</p><p>- Amounts added to provision for impairment of receivables (receivables at previous year end); and</p><p>- Amounts written off in-year (irrespective of year of recognition).</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","61601 ; 61606 ; 61639 ; 61640 ; 61641 ; 61645 ; 61646 ; 61782","2017-01-30T17:53:06.517Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678631/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678631/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678631/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Doncaster and Bassetlaw Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was reclaimed in health costs from foreign governments in each of the last three years by Doncaster and Bassetlaw Hospitals NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","61607"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678632","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>Researchers applying for funding from the Department are expected to seek best value when obtaining any medicines required for their research. This may be through existing National Health Service medicines procurement processes, or they may seek donations, or additional discounts direct from pharmaceutical suppliers if this delivers better value.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-30T15:38:05.817Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678632/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678632/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678632/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Life Sciences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how NHS processes for the purchase of medicines are taken into account in decisions of allocating funding for research and development in life sciences; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678633","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>Information regarding the number of people diagnosed with Parkinson’s disease aged 50 years and under is not collected. Parkinson’s disease predominantly affects older adults, and population prevalence estimates suggest that of the 127,000 people living with the condition in the United Kingdom, the vast majority are over the age of 50. Prevalence is highest amongst people aged over 75, and estimates suggest less than 5,000 people aged 54 years and under have the condition. More information can be found in the following prevalence study published by Parkinson’s UK:</p><p><a href="http://www.parkinsons.org.uk/sites/default/files/parkinsonsprevalenceuk_0.pdf" target="_blank">www.parkinsons.org.uk/sites/default/files/parkinsonsprevalenceuk_0.pdf</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T15:44:39.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678633/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678633/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678633/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Parkinson's Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what information his Department holds on the number of people aged 50- years and under who have Parkinson's disease.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","61574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678634","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Over one hundred homeopathic stocks are used in homeopathic medicinal products authorised or registered in the United Kingdom. The following provides a link to the Medicines and Healthcare products Regulatory Agency website page listing homeopathic medicinal products granted a registration under the Simplified Homeopathic Registration Scheme or authorisation under the Homeopathic National Rules Scheme in the UK:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/575658/HR___NR_listing_with_product_name__FINAL_.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/575658/HR___NR_listing_with_product_name__FINAL_.pdf</a></p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-02T17:56:13.543Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678634/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678634/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678634/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Homeopathy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what substances are included in the active homeopathic substances referred to in medicines and healthcare products regulatory guidance on module 3 of the homeopathic medicinal products dossier.","false","Biography information for Andrew Gwynne","Denton and Reddish","Andrew Gwynne","61600"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678635","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department, on behalf of the United Kingdom Government, reimburses other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing treatment to people we are responsible for under European Union law, irrespective of nationality. In the same way, other EEA countries and Switzerland reimburse the UK for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The requested data regarding individual trusts is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS trusts and foundation trusts publish data on amounts claimed for directly chargeable overseas patients in their annual accounts. This data does not include patients from the EEA and Switzerland whose treatment would be reimbursed under Regulations (EC) Nos 883/2004 and 987/2009. Data in trusts’ annual accounts includes:</p><p> </p><p>- Income recognised this year (invoiced amounts and accruals);</p><p>- Cash payments received in-year (invoices issued this year);</p><p>- Amounts added to provision for impairment of receivables (receivables at previous year end); and</p><p>- Amounts written off in-year (irrespective of year of recognition).</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","61606 ; 61607 ; 61639 ; 61640 ; 61641 ; 61645 ; 61646 ; 61782","2017-01-30T17:53:06.39Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678635/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678635/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678635/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Rotherham NHS Foundation Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was reclaimed in health costs from non-UK Governments in each of the last three years by the Rotherham NHS Foundation Trust.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","61601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678636","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Care Act 2014 gives local authorities the power to charge for meeting needs for care and support or support but does not give them the power to charge for carrying out a needs assessment. The Care and Support Statutory Guidance makes clear that local authorities must not charge people for a needs assessment or the preparation of a care and support plan since these processes do not constitute meeting needs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T16:03:27.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678636/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678636/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678636/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment he has made of the effect of councils charging fees to undertake needs assessments for adult social care on people with social care needs; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Barbara Keeley","Worsley and Eccles South","Barbara Keeley","61558"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678637","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>The NHS Cervical Screening Programme is directly commissioned by NHS England as part of the Section 7A agreement of the National Health Service Act 2006, as amended by the Health and Social Care Act 2012. The availability of screening within contraception and sexual health clinics, which are commissioned by local authorities, is a matter for local agreement.</p><p> </p><p>There is also the human papillomavirus (HPV) adolescent vaccination programme for girls which is well established in the United Kingdom and expected to have a significant impact on reducing cervical cancer. Since the start of the programme in 2008, more than 8.5 million doses of the HPV vaccine have been given in the UK, with close to 90% of eligible teenagers vaccinated.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-02-02T16:54:02.363Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678637/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678637/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678637/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Cervical Cancer: Screening","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, if he will make cervical screening available to women at every contraception and sexual health clinic; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir David Amess","Southend West","Sir David Amess","61552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678638","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department has made no official estimate.</p><p> </p><p>A wide range of gluten-free products are available in most supermarkets and online. The Department has made no estimate of the number of people in England unable to access gluten-free foods.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","61570","2017-01-30T16:42:19.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678638/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678638/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678638/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Coeliac Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many NHS clinical commissioning groups have a no access policy in relation to staple gluten-free substitute foods via FP10 prescription in England.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61569"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678639","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>We do not hold the data requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information is not held by individual dental surgery so it is not possible to provide information on the number of dental surgeries or the number of those that have closed.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","61554","2017-01-30T16:57:54.61Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678639/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678639/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678639/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57424, on dental services, for what reason his Department does not hold the data requested.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678640","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>We do not hold the data requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information is not held by individual dental surgery so it is not possible to provide information on the number of dental surgeries or the number of those that have closed.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","61553","2017-01-30T16:57:54.563Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678640/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678640/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678640/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Dental Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57424, how many dental surgeries there are in England.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678641","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>Patients do not have to register to receive National Health Service dental services so information is not held in the form requested.</p><p> </p><p>Information is available on the number of children receiving NHS dental services (‘patients seen’) in a 12 month period. This information is published quarterly.</p><p> </p><p>Information on children seen covers 12 months as this is the maximum intervals National Institute for Health and Care Excellence recommends for children between dental checkups.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T16:56:43.583Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678641/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678641/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678641/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Dental Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 57423, what estimate he has made of the number of children who are registered with a dentist.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61555"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678642","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The available information on the number of repeat dispensing prescription items issued in England is in the table below:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Year</p></td><td><p>Number of repeat dispensing prescription items (000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>54,061.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>64,600.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>74,879.8</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015</p></td><td><p>85,949.9</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: ePACT.net provided by the NHS Business Services Authority</p><p> </p><p>The estimated benefits of electronic repeat dispensing over single paper prescriptions is set out in the table. NHS Digital has advised that these figures represent the collective value of greater efficiency due to:</p><p>- clinical (eg general practitioner (GP)) time saved from digitally signing and cancelling electronic repeat prescriptions over the physical signature on paper prescriptions;</p><p>- prescriber administrative time savings resulting from reduced process steps for routine repeat electronic prescriptions replacing paper; and</p><p>- the reduction in the volume of paper and signing time (one digital signature per batch) over repeat prescribing in GP practices.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Financial year</p></td><td><p>Estimated benefits (£000s)</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2010-11</p></td><td><p>0</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2011-12</p></td><td><p>£290.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012-13</p></td><td><p>£3,752.7</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013-14</p></td><td><p>£21,440.5</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15</p></td><td><p>£55,876.6</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2015-16</p></td><td><p>£122,858.7</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>Source: NHS Digital</p><p>NHS England has advised that, where relevant, it is utilising every opportunity to promote and support the increased growth of the use of electronic repeat dispensing. For example the service specification for the NHS Urgent Medicine Supply advanced service pilot states that one of the aims and intended outcomes of this service is ‘to increase patients’ awareness of the electronic Repeat Dispensing Service’.</p><p> </p><p>NHS England has also been working very closely with NHS Digital, which has launched an awareness campaign to promote the use of electronic repeat dispensing. An electronic repeat dispensing toolkit along with an E-learning module to support users have been made available at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="http://www.digital.nhs.uk/eps" target="_blank">www.digital.nhs.uk/eps</a></p><p> </p><p>These have been supported with national communications and webinars. There is also a team of implementation managers supporting the roll out of electronic repeat dispensing across the country by providing support at clinical commissioning group and GP practice level and engaging local community pharmacies in the process.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T16:12:37.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678642/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678642/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678642/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Prescriptions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the (a) number of repeat dispensing prescriptions issued in England in each year from 2010 to 2015 and (b) savings made in each year as a result of repeat dispensing; and what steps the Government is taking to encourage greater use of repeat dispensing.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61571"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678643","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency is aware of one new drug product for the potential treatment of Parkinson’s disease for which a licence application submission to the European Medicines Agency is expected within the next 12 months. Details of this product are not yet in the public domain.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-01-30T15:36:38.087Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678643/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678643/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678643/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Parkinson's Disease: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what new drugs for the potential treatment of Parkinson's disease are being considered for licensing.","false","Biography information for Nick Thomas-Symonds","Torfaen","Nick Thomas-Symonds","61573"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678644","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department has made no official estimate.</p><p> </p><p>A wide range of gluten-free products are available in most supermarkets and online. The Department has made no estimate of the number of people in England unable to access gluten-free foods.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","61569","2017-01-30T16:42:19.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678644/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678644/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678644/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Coeliac Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of people in England diagnosed with coeliac disease who are unable to access staple gluten-free substitute foods.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61570"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678645","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Public Health England (PHE) recognises the role that access to nature and open spaces play in the health and wellbeing of populations and commissioned the Institute of Health Equity to do an evidence review on <em>Improving Access to Open Space</em> which can be accessed using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/357411/Review8_Green_spaces_health_inequalities.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/357411/Review8_Green_spaces_health_inequalities.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>PHE is not aware of any evidence relating specifically to country parks and its effect on health.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","61678","2017-02-02T17:51:53.833Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678645/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678645/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678645/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Country Parks: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of access to country parks on children's health and well-being.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","61677"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678646","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>Public Health England (PHE) recognises the role that access to nature and open spaces play in the health and wellbeing of populations and commissioned the Institute of Health Equity to do an evidence review on <em>Improving Access to Open Space</em> which can be accessed using the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/357411/Review8_Green_spaces_health_inequalities.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/357411/Review8_Green_spaces_health_inequalities.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>PHE is not aware of any evidence relating specifically to country parks and its effect on health.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","61677","2017-02-02T17:51:53.897Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678646/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678646/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678646/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Country Parks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect of access to country parks on health inequalities.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","61678"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678647","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Department has not made an assessment of the effect of 20 minutes brisk walking on health improvement.</p><p> </p><p>According to United Kingdom Chief Medical Officers' guidelines for physical activity, all adults should be active for at least 150 minutes each week of moderate to vigorous intensity physical activity.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-02T17:53:01.787Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678647/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678647/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678647/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Walking","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what assessment his Department has made of the effect that 20 minutes of brisk walking has on improving health.","false","Biography information for Margaret Greenwood","Wirral West","Margaret Greenwood","61679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678648","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department does not hold the total number of community hospitals centrally.</p><p> </p><p>However, there are currently 28 community hospitals across Devon, with four community hospitals in the East Devon constituency.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2017-01-30T15:51:47.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678648/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678648/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678648/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Community Hospitals: Devon","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what proportion of community hospitals are in (a) Devon and (b) East Devon.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","61649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678649","HM Treasury","false","2017-02-02","<p>The joint HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC)/Border Force strategy ('Tackling Illicit Tobacco: From leaf to light') ‎published on GOV.UK on 24 March 2015 sets out a comprehensive framework to tackle this problem at all points in the supply chain, to deter and punish involvement in the fraud and reduce demand. HMRC and Border Force work closely with other enforcement agencies, including Trading Standards and the police to target those involved in the fraud. Since 2000, the illicit market for cigarettes has reduced from 22% to 13% and for hand rolling tobacco from 61% to 32%.</p><p> </p><p>There is a wide range of sanctions available to tackle the sale of illicit tobacco (and alcohol) including seizure of products and cash, financial penalties and a maximum penalty of seven year’s imprisonment. In the last two years alone, over 3.5 billion illicit cigarettes and around 600 tonnes of hand-rolling tobacco have been seized resulting in 848 prosecutions.</p><p> </p><p>On prosecution, HMRC can also apply for withdrawal of retailers' alcohol licenses and orders prohibiting the use of premises for the sale of tobacco for a period of up to 6 months. Additionally, as a result of coordinated activity with other enforcement agencies, action can be taken on wider tobacco offences, such as under-age sales, and on vehicle licensing and immigration offences.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC works to raise awareness of the consequences of participation in the illicit market, its links with organised criminality and the related harm that illicit tobacco causes to individuals, communities and legitimate high street businesses. HMRC has been using behavioural insight to better promote awareness of the issue and deter participation in the fraud, for example through campaigns it has undertaken involving hauliers, coach drivers and retailers.</p><p> </p><p>As announced at Budget 2016, following the informal consultation HMRC is currently developing options, with particular focus on the approach taken to repeat offenders, and plans to consult formally later this year.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","61623 ; 61626","2017-02-02T16:33:17.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678649/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678649/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678649/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-25","Tobacco","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce demand for illicit tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","61624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678650","Department of Health","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Department, on behalf of the United Kingdom Government, reimburses other European Economic Area (EEA) countries and Switzerland for the cost of providing treatment to people we are responsible for under European Union law, irrespective of nationality. In the same way, other EEA countries and Switzerland reimburse the UK for the cost of the National Health Service providing treatment to people they are responsible for under EU law, including UK nationals insured in another EEA country or Switzerland.</p><p> </p><p>The requested data regarding individual trusts is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>NHS trusts and foundation trusts publish data on amounts claimed for directly chargeable overseas patients in their annual accounts. This data does not include patients from the EEA and Switzerland whose treatment would be reimbursed under Regulations (EC) Nos 883/2004 and 987/2009. Data in trusts’ annual accounts includes:</p><p> </p><p>- Income recognised this year (invoiced amounts and accruals);</p><p>- Cash payments received in-year (invoices issued this year);</p><p>- Amounts added to provision for impairment of receivables (receivables at previous year end); and</p><p>- Amounts written off in-year (irrespective of year of recognition).</p><p> </p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne","61601 ; 61606 ; 61607 ; 61640 ; 61641 ; 61645 ; 61646 ; 61782","2017-01-30T17:53:06.577Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678650/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678650/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678650/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Leeds General Infirmary","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much was reclaimed in costs to the NHS from foreign governments by Leeds General Infirmary in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","61639"
