is currently developing options, with particular focus on the approach taken to repeat offenders, and plans to consult formally later this year.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison","61624 ; 61626","2017-02-02T16:33:17.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678673/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678673/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678673/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2017-01-25","Tobacco: Smuggling","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to reduce the sale of illicit tobacco.","false","Biography information for Mr Virendra Sharma","Ealing, Southall","Mr Virendra Sharma","61623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678674","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer provided by the Minister of State for Security during Home Office Oral Answers to Questions on Monday 23 January 2017 (908280, Volume 620, column 7).</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-30T14:35:53.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678674/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678674/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678674/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","Culture, Practices and Ethics of the Press Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what discussions she has had with Cabinet colleagues on when to commence the second part of the Leveson inquiry; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Julie Elliott","Sunderland Central","Julie Elliott","61700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678675","Home Office","false","2017-02-02","<p>Between 2010-11 and 2014-15, the Home Office provided Crimestoppers with grant funding of £900,000 per annum. As part of wider Government efficiency measures, Crimestoppers’ grant funding was reduced by 5% in 2015-16 and 2016-17, to £855,000 and £770,000 per annum respectively. Crimestoppers separately receives funding from a range of other public bodies, including Police and Crime Commissioners.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-02-02T17:03:03.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678675/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678675/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678675/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","Crimestoppers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what changes in funding from the public purse to Crimestoppers were made in each year from 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","61699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678676","Home Office","false","2017-02-06","<p>All financial data is released on a financial year basis, and will only be available once the 2016-17 Home Office Annual Report and Accounts have been drafted, and then audited by the National Audit Office (NAO).</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2017-02-06T13:58:46.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678676/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678676/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678676/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","British Nationality: Fees and Charges","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how much was accrued to the public purse in nationality fees in 2016.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","61632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678677","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>It is an operational decision for Chief Constables, working with their applicable Police and Crime Commissioner to determine the levels of resources required for the police to monitor and manage such events.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-30T11:50:49.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678677/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678677/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678677/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","Fracking: Demonstrations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the cost of monitoring and policing anti-fracking protests since 2010 in (a) Lancashire and (b) the UK.","false","Biography information for Graham P Jones","Hyndburn","Graham Jones","61635"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678678","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Home Office is in the process of recruiting a new Chief Scientific Advisor at the moment. A suitable candidate will be appointed as soon as is practicable. As with any recruitment process the timescale for filling the vacancy is dependent upon attracting and selecting a suitable candidate, notice periods, and completion of pre-employment and security checks.</p>","Truro and Falmouth","Sarah Newton",,"2017-01-30T11:50:00.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678678/answer","Biography information for Sarah Newton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678678/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678678/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","Home Office: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the term of office of the current Chief Scientific Adviser to her Department ends; and what the timescale will be for filling that vacancy when it arises.","true","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","61633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678679","Home Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>Each year the National Crime Agency publishes statistics on the number of European Arrest Warrants (EAW) issued by the UK.</p><p>These figures include a breakdown of the number of EAWs by the UK requesting law enforcement agency, including by Police Force. These figures are published at: -</p><p><a href="http://www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics" target="_blank">www.nationalcrimeagency.gov.uk/publications/european-arrest-warrant-statistics</a></p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2017-01-30T11:27:47.397Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678679/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678679/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678679/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2017-01-25","European Arrest Warrants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many European Arrest Warrant requests have been made by UK police forces to each of the other EU countries in the last five years; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","61591"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678680","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-30","<p>In 2016, 15 prisoners in England and Wales sought transfer to prisons in the Republic of Ireland. Transfers of prisoners from Scotland and from Northern Ireland are the responsibility of the relevant devolved authorities.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-01-30T17:52:37.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678680/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678680/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678680/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Prisoners' Transfers: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many Irish citizens in prison within the UK have requested transfers to prisons in the Republic of Ireland in the last 12 months; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Lady Hermon","North Down","Lady Hermon","61592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678682","House of Commons Commission","false","2017-01-30","<p>Members are encouraged to report all social media abuse and threats to the Parliamentary Liaison and Investigation Team (PLAIT), based in Westminster. This police unit provides support to individual Members about security concerns and co-ordinates the response with local forces.</p><p>The House has a policy of not commenting publicly on specific security matters. However, the Parliamentary Security Director is happy to meet the right hon. Member to discuss the level of online abuse of female hon. Members.</p><p>The Parliamentary Security Department, in conjunction with the police digital crime unit and social media companies, have run workshops for Members on this issue and provides general security advice on social media harassment.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2017-01-30T12:05:54.433Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678682/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678682/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678682/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2017-01-25","Members: Harassment","1","House of Commons","To ask the right hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington, representing the House of Commons Commission, what recent assessment the Commission has made of the level of online abuse of female hon. Members.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","61644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678683","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-01","<p>DFID supports HALO Trust’s programmes in Burma, Zimbabwe, South Sudan, Cambodia, Somalia and Afghanistan. We do not currently work with HALO in Colombia. In 2016, DFID’s programmes cleared mines and other explosive remnants of war from over 2,000 hectares of land, which were returned back to productive use, saving lives and supporting livelihoods.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-01T17:57:13.02Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678683/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678683/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678683/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-25","Colombia: Halo Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, whether the Halo Trust is working on behalf of the Government in carrying out its de-mining work in Colombia; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Clive Efford","Eltham","Clive Efford","61682"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678684","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-01","<p>It is too early to put an exact figure on the financial impact of the restoration of the Mexico City Policy.</p><p>The UK firmly believes that supporting comprehensive sexual and reproductive health and rights of women and girls, through proven, evidence-based public health interventions, saves lives and supports prosperity. We will continue to work with all our partners, including governments, UNFPA and civil society partners, to deliver this.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-01T17:24:15.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678684/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678684/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678684/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-25","Developing Countries: Family Planning","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what estimate her Department has made of the potential shortfall in funding to charities and non-governmental organisations as a result of the revocation in the US of the Presidential Memorandum of 23 January 2009 Mexico City Policy and Assistance for Voluntary Population Planning and the reinstatement of the Presidential Memorandum of 22 January 2001 Restoration of Mexico City Policy; and what plans her Department has to ensure continued access to (a) family planning advice and (b) safe termination and contraception through its programmes.","false","Biography information for Dr Sarah Wollaston","Totnes","Dr Sarah Wollaston","61717"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678685","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-01","<p>The World Food Programme (WFP) has trialled the use of Joint Precision Airdrop System (JPADS) as part of its humanitarian airdrop operations to Deir Ez-Zour. WFP report that the cost of JPADS was roughly 3.5 times higher than non-guided parachutes, and that the average percentage of goods recovered from 27 JPADS airdrops was lower than the average for non-guided parachutes.</p><p>The UK does not possess a JPADS capability. We continue to work with partners to explore all viable options for delivering aid into besieged areas in Syria. Aid, delivered by road, by trusted humanitarian partners who can ensure it gets to those who need it most, remains the most effective approach.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2017-02-01T17:58:41.383Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678685/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678685/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678685/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-25","Syria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made on the success of the World Food Programme's use of the Joint Precision Airdrop System (JPADS) for aid air-drops into Deir Ezzor; and what steps her Department has taken to assess the feasibility of the Government using JPADS for aid air-drops into besieged areas of Syria.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","61715"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678686","Department for International Development","false","2017-02-01","<p>In order to ensure that DFID strategy overseas is informed by issues on the ground a series of <em>Country Poverty Reduction Diagnostics</em> were conducted. These directly informed the <em>Bilateral Development Review</em>. These diagnostics include analyses of country specific issues, including demographic challenges which the country is experiencing or expecting to experience during the course of this strategic planning period.</p>","Stockton South","James Wharton",,"2017-02-01T17:27:59.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678686/answer","Biography information for James Wharton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678686/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678686/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2017-01-25","Developing Countries: Older People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, with reference to her Department's Bilateral Development Review 2016, how the analysis of demographic trends took into account the ageing population in developing countries.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","61636"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678687","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-31","<p>HM Courts &amp; Tribunals Service keeps its operational estate under review to make sure that it aligns with the delivery of reformed court and tribunal services. Any new proposals to close courts will be subject to public consultation.</p><p> </p><p>We are building a justice system which is simpler, swifter and more efficient. Our estate is a major asset, and in an increasingly digital world, we are looking at how we use our buildings to deliver the best possible service to our users now and in the future.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-31T15:19:44.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678687/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678687/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678687/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Courts and Tribunals: Buildings","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what plans she has for the future of the courts and tribunals estate in England and Wales; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","61539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678688","Department of Health","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Children and Young People’s Mental Health Services Transformation Programme is improving mental health outcomes for children and young people. Within the Programme, the Health and Justice and Specialised Commissioning Children and Young People’s Mental Health Services Transformation Workstream is responding to challenges around the commissioning and provision of mental health services for those held in the children and young people’s secure estate (CYPSE), including testing and evaluating the Secure Stairs integrated framework of care across the CYPSE.</p><p> </p><p>The Workstream is also targeting improved mental health service provision for children and young people coming into contact with other elements of the health and justice pathway, such as Liaison and Diversion services, Sexual Assault Referral Centres and crisis care related to police custody.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2017-02-02T17:56:18.73Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678688/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678688/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678688/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2017-01-25","Young Offenders: Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent steps he has taken on improving mental health support for young offenders.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678689","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government values the role paralegals play.</p><p> </p><p>The legal profession in England and Wales is independent of Government, and under the Legal Services Act 2007, only a person authorised by an approved regulator may provide a reserved legal activity.</p><p> </p><p>The 2007 Act provides the powers for the Legal Services Board to make recommendations to government for bodies to be designated as approved regulators, and it has not made a recommendation in respect of the Professional Paralegal Register. The government has no plans to make such a designation without having had a recommendation.</p><p> </p><p>My department has not had any recent discussions with representatives of paralegals about either their approach to sector self-regulation or the possibility of the Professional Paralegal Register being designated as an approved regulator under the Legal Services Act 2007.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","61616 ; 61617","2017-02-03T14:34:28.737Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678689/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678689/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678689/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions she has had with (a) representatives of the paralegal profession, (b) the Professional Paralegal Register and (c) the Institute of Paralegals on the effectiveness of the registration system for that profession.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","61615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678690","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government values the role paralegals play.</p><p> </p><p>The legal profession in England and Wales is independent of Government, and under the Legal Services Act 2007, only a person authorised by an approved regulator may provide a reserved legal activity.</p><p> </p><p>The 2007 Act provides the powers for the Legal Services Board to make recommendations to government for bodies to be designated as approved regulators, and it has not made a recommendation in respect of the Professional Paralegal Register. The government has no plans to make such a designation without having had a recommendation.</p><p> </p><p>My department has not had any recent discussions with representatives of paralegals about either their approach to sector self-regulation or the possibility of the Professional Paralegal Register being designated as an approved regulator under the Legal Services Act 2007.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","61615 ; 61617","2017-02-03T14:34:28.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678690/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678690/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678690/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she has had with the Professional Paralegal Register on the level of registration on that register since that body was created.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","61616"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678691","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Government values the role paralegals play.</p><p> </p><p>The legal profession in England and Wales is independent of Government, and under the Legal Services Act 2007, only a person authorised by an approved regulator may provide a reserved legal activity.</p><p> </p><p>The 2007 Act provides the powers for the Legal Services Board to make recommendations to government for bodies to be designated as approved regulators, and it has not made a recommendation in respect of the Professional Paralegal Register. The government has no plans to make such a designation without having had a recommendation.</p><p> </p><p>My department has not had any recent discussions with representatives of paralegals about either their approach to sector self-regulation or the possibility of the Professional Paralegal Register being designated as an approved regulator under the Legal Services Act 2007.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee","61615 ; 61616","2017-02-03T14:34:28.847Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678691/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678691/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678691/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Legal Profession","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will add the Professional Paralegal Register to the statutory list of approved regulators under the Legal Services Act 2007.","false","Biography information for Kate Hoey","Vauxhall","Kate Hoey","61617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678692","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Youth Justice Board is currently developing links with StreetGames along with other community based organisations, to develop initiatives to engage young offenders in sports and work programmes upon release from custody, in order to prevent reoffending and support their rehabilitation.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-03T14:27:15.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678692/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678692/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678692/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Sports: Young People","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will make it her policy to increase public funding for the Streetgames programme.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61619"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678693","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government is committed to developing traineeship and apprenticeship pathways for young offenders across a variety of sectors with a range of potential employers. We have not had specific discussions with Network Rail but this will be something we will be exploring as part of ongoing work.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-02T14:52:23.623Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678693/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678693/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678693/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Young Offenders: Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what recent discussions she has had with Network Rail on engineering apprenticeships for youth offenders.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678694","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-01","<p>Certain HMCTS staff are already authorised to exercise judicial powers across most jurisdictions. Mechanisms are in place to discuss training and remuneration with the staff involved and with trades unions. There have been numerous discussions under this framework in the past, as roles have changed and developed.</p><p> </p><p>HMCTS recently sought the views of staff, trades unions and the judiciary about a proposed new senior leadership structure for these roles, and will continue to use the mechanisms available as they develop.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-01T16:59:54.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678694/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678694/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678694/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Courts: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what discussions she has had with court staff trade union representatives on their remuneration and training for judicial decision-making as set out in the Transforming our Justice System, consultation paper, published in September 2016.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","61551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678695","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government plans to publish its legislative proposals shortly.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-30T17:24:44.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678695/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678695/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678695/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Personal Injury: Compensation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, when the Government plans to publish its legislative proposals stemming from its consultation, Reforming the Soft Tissue Injury (Whiplash) Claims Process, of November 2016.","false","Biography information for Christina Rees","Neath","Christina Rees","61550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678696","Attorney General","false","2017-02-15","<p>All decisions by the prosecution are made in accordance with the Code for Crown Prosecutors which sets out a Full Code Test that applies at all stages of any prosecution.</p><p> </p><p>In addition to the principles set out in the Code, a prosecutor considering a plea offered by the defence will have regard to the Attorney General's Guidelines on the Acceptance of Pleas and the Prosecutor's Role in the Sentencing Exercise [2009] and the Attorney General’s Guidelines on Plea Discussions in cases of serious or complex fraud (where appropriate).</p><p> </p><p>The Full Code Test states that a prosecution will only proceed if the prosecutor finds sufficient evidence for a realistic prospect of conviction and that a prosecution is in the public interest. As such a prosecutor will assess the acceptability of a plea to determine whether it accords with the broad extent of the criminality that met the evidential stage of the Full Code test.</p><p> </p><p>If this stage is met the prosecutor will further consider whether it is in the public interest to accept the plea. In addition the prosecutor will ensure that the basis of a guilty plea is not based on a misleading or untrue set of facts and that proper account is taken of the victim's interests prior to any plea being accepted. The Code is clear that prosecutors should only accept such pleas if the court is able to pass a sentence that matches the seriousness of the offending.</p><p> </p><p>Neither the Crown Prosecution Service nor the Serious Fraud Office maintain a central record of cases involving the acceptance of a guilty plea to some or alternative charges, or whether they were accepted on a particular basis. This information could only be obtained by examining CPS or SFO case files, which would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Kenilworth and Southam","Jeremy Wright",,"2017-02-15T16:34:52.447Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678696/answer","Biography information for Jeremy Wright","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678696/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678696/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2017-01-25","Plea Bargaining","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what information his Department holds on the number of plea bargains offered to defendants in England since 2010.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678697","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-16","<p>The information requested is available on GOV.UK.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-16T11:29:21.983Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678697/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678697/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678697/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Prisoners: Education and Training","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how much was spent on education and training for prisoners in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","61751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678698","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Government’s view is that when there is a dispute about child arrangements and a parent asks a court to determine those arrangements, the existing law provides a framework which best serves the interests of both children and parents. If the court determines that a shared residence arrangement is necessary to meet the child’s welfare needs it can make an order to that effect.</p><p> </p><p>While the welfare of the child is the courts paramount consideration, the court must by law presume that the involvement of a parent in the life of the child concerned will further that child’s welfare, unless the contrary can be shown. The nature and extent of that involvement will then be determined by the court based on the facts in each case.</p><p> </p><p>In determining the child’s welfare needs the court will apply the factors set out in the ‘welfare checklist’ in the Children Act 1989. These include the ascertainable wishes and feelings of the child concerned, the impact on the child of any change in circumstances, and how capable each parent is of meeting the child’s needs. The court will also consider any harm the child has suffered or is at risk of suffering, which could include any harm from witnessing domestic violence.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-01-30T17:25:41.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678698/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678698/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678698/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Children: Custody","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, if she will take steps to introduce guidance for courts on providing both parents with 50-50 access to their children on divorce as a default unless specific circumstances demonstrate otherwise; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","61660"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678699","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-16","<p>We carefully study the details of all deaths in custody to determine whether there are any patterns, or lessons to be learned, to further our understanding of why these tragic events happen.</p><p> </p><p>We have put in place a range of measures to help to support prisoners who are at risk of self-harm or suicide, especially in the first 24 hours when prisoners are at their most vulnerable. We are also investing in mental health awareness training for staff.</p>","East Surrey","Mr Sam Gyimah",,"2017-02-16T11:42:40.393Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678699/answer","Biography information for Mr Sam Gyimah","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678699/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678699/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Prisons: Suicide","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, with reference to the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State's oral contribution of 24 January 2017, Official Report, column 156, when she plans to publish the findings of her investigation into self-inflicted deaths in prisons.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","61605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678700","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-02","<p>Data on the number of youth offenders who have participated in the Duke of Edinburgh’s Award scheme each year since 2010 is not held centrally.</p><p> </p><p>We recognise the positive impact the award has and are working with education providers and the National Offender Management Service to deliver The Award in Youth Offending Institutions and Secure Training Centres.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-02T14:54:49.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678700/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678700/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678700/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Young Offenders: Duke of Edinburgh's Award Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many youth offenders have participated in the Duke of Edinburgh Award Scheme in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678701","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-09","<p>From 1 January 2015 to 30 September 2016 the number and proportion of appeals listed and disposed of taking more than 12 months was 24,319 (20%) in the First-tier Tribunal and 714 (5%) in the Upper Tribunal.</p><p>HM Courts and Tribunals Service does everything it can to avoid unnecessary delay in the Immigration and Asylum Chamber and has provided an additional 4,950 tribunal sitting days for this financial year to reduce caseloads.</p>","North East Hertfordshire","Sir Oliver Heald",,"2017-02-09T18:22:56.357Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678701/answer","Biography information for Sir Oliver Heald","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678701/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678701/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Immigration: Appeals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, (a) how many and (b) what proportion of appeals listed by the (a) first-tier and (b) upper tribunal of the Immigration and Asylum Chamber since 2015 have taken more than 12 months to be heard; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Gareth Thomas","Harrow West","Gareth Thomas","61796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678702","Ministry of Justice","false","2017-02-03","<p>The Ministry of Justice does not have a vacancy for the post of Chief Scientific Adviser. Osama Rahman, Director of Analysis and Chief Economist, is the Chief Scientific Adviser for the Ministry of Justice.</p>","Bracknell","Dr Phillip Lee",,"2017-02-03T14:25:25.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678702/answer","Biography information for Dr Phillip Lee","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678702/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678702/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2017-01-25","Ministry of Justice: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for how long the post of Chief Scientific Adviser to her Department has been vacant; and what plans she has to advertise for and fill that vacancy.","true","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","61771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678703","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>The Northern Ireland Office does not have a post of Chief Scientific Adviser.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-01-30T11:41:36.207Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678703/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678703/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678703/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-25","Northern Ireland Office: Chief Scientific Advisers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, for how long the post of Chief Scientific Adviser to his Department has been vacant; and what plans he has to advertise for and fill that vacancy.","true","Biography information for Stephen Metcalfe","South Basildon and East Thurrock","Stephen Metcalfe","61770"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678704","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-02-01","<p>Integrated Education is a devolved matter and is primarily the responsibility for the Northern Ireland Minister of Education. It is for him and his department to assess the effectiveness of the programmes which are in place.</p><p> </p><p>However, this Government recognises the important contribution which integrated education has to play in promoting reconciliation and mutual understanding and is committed to supporting the Northern Ireland Executive in delivering its objectives in this important area. The Stormont House and Fresh Start Agreements identified up to £500 million of capital funding over 10 years to support shared and integrated education, and shared housing.</p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-02-01T15:05:53.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678704/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678704/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678704/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-25","Schools: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment he has made of the effectiveness of integrated schooling programmes in Northern Ireland in promoting community cohesion since 2013.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61737"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678705","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>It would not be appropriate for the Government to comment on specific recommendations. The Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland’s review is ongoing and the public consultation on its provisional proposals concluded in November 2016. The Commission will publish all responses received in due course as part of a 4 week consultation during which written submissions on the responses are invited.</p><p> </p>","Keighley","Kris Hopkins",,"2017-01-30T11:43:12.16Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678705/answer","Biography information for Kris Hopkins","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678705/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678705/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-25","Constituencies: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the recommendations of the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland on political stability in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Dr Andrew Murrison","South West Wiltshire","Dr Andrew Murrison","61730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678706","Northern Ireland Office","false","2017-01-30","<p>Through my Business Advisory Group that I established in September, I and my Ministerial colleagues have had regular meetings with businesses in Northern Ireland. The Group brings together representatives from a broad range of sectors, to discuss a range of economic issues, including the impact and opportunities of the UK’s exit from the European Union. I will continue to meet businesses to ensure that their views are reflected in the process of exiting the European Union, so that we build a strong and prosperous economy in Northern Ireland that works for everyone.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2017-01-30T15:08:03.927Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678706/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678706/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678706/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2017-01-25","Business: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what recent meetings he has had with businesses in Northern Ireland to discuss the UK's exit from the EU.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","61578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678707","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-31","<p>Prior to conducting a test fire of a Trident missile, the UK strictly adheres to all relevant treaty obligations, notifying relevant nations and interested parties of the test in advance.</p><p>There is no set approach to announcing the outcome of a Demonstration and Shakedown Operation. This is decided on a case by case basis and is informed by the circumstances at the time.</p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon",,"2017-01-31T16:00:54.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678707/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678707/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678707/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-25","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what criteria the Government uses to determine whether to announce the (a) date and (b) outcome of tests of Trident missiles.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","61728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678708","Prime Minister","false","2017-01-30","<p>I discussed a range of issues with President Trump, including defence and security issues. The UK Government remains determined to continue to work with partners across the international community to prevent proliferation and to make progress on multilateral nuclear disarmament.</p>","Maidenhead","Mrs Theresa May",,"2017-01-30T16:02:25.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678708/answer","Biography information for Mrs Theresa May","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678708/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678708/answer",,,,,"23","Prime Minister","Prime Minister","2017-01-25","USA: Nuclear Disarmament","1","House of Commons","To ask the Prime Minister, what plans she has to discuss with President Trump his policy on reducing nuclear weapons through negotiations during her forthcoming visit to the US.","false","Biography information for Kelvin Hopkins","Luton North","Kelvin Hopkins","61754"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678709","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>Highways England recognises the appearance of general inactivity on roadworks is a concern for road users and is making improvements in informing its customers what works are happening, why and what benefits are expected.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, they are also looking at more efficient ways of working to make best use of lane closures to increase productivity and minimise the duration and impact of roadworks on their customers.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T13:57:47.323Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678709/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678709/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678709/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Roads: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what steps his Department is taking to reduce the number of roadworks sites which are unmanned overnight and at weekends.","false","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson","61780"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678710","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>It is the Government’s intention that properties acquired under the various HS2 compensation schemes and that are not required for construction of the railway will be returned to the housing market. Where this occurs properties will be sold at market value.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-02T14:38:27.147Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678710/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678710/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678710/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, whether funds paid out to properties under the HS2 Exceptional Hardship Scheme or Need to Sell Scheme which no longer fulfil the criteria of those schemes where the route of High Speed 2 is changed will be recovered.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","61783"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678711","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Government recognises that proposals for HS2 can cause uncertainty for individuals, communities and small businesses and has had an effect on property prices in the vicinity of the route. As a result it launched an Exceptional Hardship Scheme (EHS) to assist those most affected to sell their home to Government at its unblighted market value.</p><p> </p><p>The average amount paid out under the HS2 Exceptional Hardship Scheme is £629,395.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-02T14:48:06.537Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678711/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678711/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678711/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","High Speed 2 Railway Line","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the average amount is that has been paid out to people under the HS2 Exceptional Hardship Scheme.","false","Biography information for Keith Vaz","Leicester East","Keith Vaz","61784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678712","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-30","<p>Over £40 million a year of Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) is already devolved to local transport authorities in England outside London. So, for instance, Devon County Council receives over £1.1 million in devolved BSOG each year. Authorities have freedom to decide how they use the devolved funding, as long as it is used to support the provision of bus services in their area.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to continue to consider any further requests for the devolution of BSOG, other than where franchising is in place, on a case by case basis – with a focus on the benefits to be achieved for passengers. However, we believe that simply devolving all BSOG automatically to local authorities could have perverse and unintended outcomes for local bus services, as such services do not respect local transport authority boundaries and the decisions taken by one authority could have significant implications for the overall viability of a wider network of services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","61650","2017-01-30T14:12:30.963Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678712/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678712/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678712/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if he will take steps to allow (a) Devon County Council and (b) other councils to decide how and where to spend the Bus Service Operators Grant.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","61745"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678713","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>On 26 January 2017, the Department for Transport announced the outcome of the Access Fund, a £60 million revenue competition which was open to all local transport authorities within England (outside London).</p><p> </p><p>A full list of the successful bids and the amounts of funding awarded is available at the link below.</p><p>Access Fund: funding decisions 2017 to 2020<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-fund-funding-decisions-2017-to-2020" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/access-fund-funding-decisions-2017-to-2020</a></p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2017-02-02T15:16:36.1Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678713/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678713/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678713/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Cycling and Walking: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which local authorities were successful in their bids for the Access Fund for funding to improve access to jobs and education through cycling and walking; and how much funding each authority secured.","false","Biography information for Daniel Zeichner","Cambridge","Daniel Zeichner","61727"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678714","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Air Accidents Investigation Branch (AAIB) assesses whether responses to recommendations meet the intent of the recommendations and publishes its findings in an Annual Safety Report (previously named the Progress Report) on its website <a href="http://www.aaib.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.aaib.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>The AAIB does not monitor the implementation of safety recommendations. It is the responsibility of the regulatory authorities, in this case the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA), to monitor the implementation and the effectiveness of recommendations made by the AAIB.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T11:47:13.507Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678714/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678714/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678714/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Helicopters: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what analysis of the effectiveness of additional gearbox condition monitoring on the AS332 L2 and the EC225 was undertaken by (a) his Department and (b) regulatory authorities after the accident at Peterhead on 1 April 2009.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","61738"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678715","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Air Accidents Investigation Branch (AAIB) made 17 recommendations as a result of its investigation into the accident to Aerospatiale (Eurocopter) AS332 L2 Super Puma, G-REDL on 1 April 2009. Of these two remain “open”.</p><p> </p><p>The AAIB assesses whether responses to recommendations meet the intent of the recommendations and publishes its findings in an Annual Safety Report (previously named the Progress Report) on its website <a href="http://www.aaib.gov.uk" target="_blank">www.aaib.gov.uk</a></p><p> </p><p>The AAIB does not monitor the implementation of safety recommendations.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T12:36:02.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678715/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678715/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678715/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Helicopters: Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what monitoring his Department has undertaken of implementation of the Air Accident Investigation Branch's safety recommendations made as a result of its report on the accident at Peterhead on 1 April 2009.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","61739"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678716","Department for Transport","false","2017-02-02","<p>The Civil Aviation Authority are committed to the safety of oil and gas workers and continue to engage with the industry to ensure that these aircraft are safe. The Offshore Helicopter Safety Leadership Group (OHSLG), made up of helicopter operators, unions, member-organisations and the Civil Aviation Authority as the UK’s independent aviation safety regulator, works to ensure that offshore workers receive timely and accurate information on offshore helicopter safety.</p><p> </p><p>The latest example of this was the recent safety inspections of the Sikorsky S92 helicopter, where OHSLG members met in January and worked together to ensure the offshore workforce received immediate information on the inspections, their context and what they involved.</p>","South Holland and The Deepings","Mr John Hayes",,"2017-02-02T11:39:32.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678716/answer","Biography information for Sir John Hayes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678716/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678716/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Helicopters: North Sea","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions his Department has had with helicopter operators and manufacturers on steps to reassure workers in the North Sea about the maintenance and operational record of the helicopter fleet.","false","Biography information for Drew Hendry","Inverness, Nairn, Badenoch and Strathspey","Drew Hendry","61726"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678717","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-30","<p>This is a complex claim to analyse and the process is still ongoing. The Department is currently discussing the claim with Govia Thameslink Railway and considering the points made by the operator before making its determination.</p>","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard",,"2017-01-30T14:36:34.603Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678717/answer","Biography information for Paul Maynard","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678717/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678717/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Govia Thameslink Railway","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, when his Department plans to make a final decision on Govia Thameslink Railway's existing force majeure claims.","false","Biography information for Andy McDonald","Middlesbrough","Andy McDonald","61654"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678718","Department for Transport","false","2017-01-30","<p>Over £40 million a year of Bus Service Operators Grant (BSOG) is already devolved to local transport authorities in England outside London. So, for instance, Devon County Council receives over £1.1 million in devolved BSOG each year. Authorities have freedom to decide how they use the devolved funding, as long as it is used to support the provision of bus services in their area.</p><p> </p><p>We intend to continue to consider any further requests for the devolution of BSOG, other than where franchising is in place, on a case by case basis – with a focus on the benefits to be achieved for passengers. However, we believe that simply devolving all BSOG automatically to local authorities could have perverse and unintended outcomes for local bus services, as such services do not respect local transport authority boundaries and the decisions taken by one authority could have significant implications for the overall viability of a wider network of services.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones","61745","2017-01-30T14:12:30.917Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678718/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678718/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678718/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2017-01-25","Bus Service Operators Grant","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, if his Department will assess the potential merits of allowing local authorities to take responsibility for the Bus Service Operators Grant.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","61650"
