"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677991","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-27","<p>No UK Government Ministers attended the Demonstration and Shakedown Operations (DASO) in the US in 2012 and 2016. Overall, 30 UK personnel attended the 2012 DASO and 42 attended in 2016. All attendees required accommodation in US hotels for periods of between two and four nights depending on whether they were witnessing rehearsal activity and the launch or only the launch.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, eight guests were invited on board the HMS Vigilant; three military and five civilians. Three of these guests were considered VIPs. In 2016, seven guests were invited on board HMS Vengeance; four military and three civilians. Three of these guests were considered VIPs.</p><p> </p><p>In 2012, eleven civilian guests, including UK Government officials, industrial partners and academics, attended the DASO on board the Launch Area Surface Ship, and 28 civilians attended the DASO in 2016.</p><p> </p>","Sevenoaks","Sir Michael Fallon","61391 ; 61392 ; 61399 ; 61401 ; 61448","2017-01-27T14:48:25.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677991/answer","Biography information for Sir Michael Fallon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677991/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677991/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Trident Missiles: Testing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many UK personnel attended Royal Navy SSBN and Trident II D5 demonstration and shakedown operations in (a) 2012 and (b) 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Kevan Jones","North Durham","Mr Kevan Jones","61405"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677992","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>In training year 2015-2016, 14,562 trainees arrived at the Defence School of Transport (DST) to conduct training. During this period, the school offered 129 courses. The planned Babcock contract extension to cover the provision of equipment support at the DST is still being finalised. There are currently 683 civil service posts, and 177 military posts at the DST.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-01T16:31:09.267Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677992/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677992/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677992/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Defence School of Transport","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, how many trainees have been admitted to training courses at the Defence School of Transport, Leconfield in the fiscal year (a) before and (b) since Babock International took over the contract for the running of the facilities; how many training courses have been offered in each such year; and how many staff were employed in each such year.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","61406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677993","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-31","<p>Royal Marines Tamar, located within HM Naval Base Devonport, was established in August 2013 as the Amphibious Centre of Excellence incorporating 1 Assault Group Royal Marines and 539 Assault Squadron. It is now responsible for the training and delivery of all Landing craft and crews. Any further moves of Royal Marines Units are under review as part of the Defence estate optimisation strategy 'Better Defence Estate'.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-31T16:05:07.52Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677993/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677993/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677993/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Devonport Dockyard","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what his proposed timetable is to establish Plymouth as an amphibious Centre of Excellence; and when he expects the relocation of various regiments to take place.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","61373"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677994","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-02-01","<p>The Future Anti-Surface Guided Weapons programme will provide the Royal Navy with Sea Venom and Martlet missiles, both of which can be launched from helicopters.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2017-02-01T16:31:34Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677994/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677994/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677994/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Guided Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what plans he has for the provision of helicopter-borne anti-ship missiles for the Royal Navy after the withdrawal from service of Sea Skua missiles.","false","Biography information for Jack Lopresti","Filton and Bradley Stoke","Jack Lopresti","61360"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677995","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-31","<p>Parliament will be updated annually on the progress of our 'Better Defence Estate' strategy. This will include updates to the reprovision plan on a rolling five-year basis.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-31T16:03:23.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677995/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677995/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677995/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Marines","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, if he will discuss with hon. Members representing all affected constituencies his plans for the Royal Marine relocations before making final decisions.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","61363"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677996","Ministry of Defence","false","2017-01-31","<p>The 'Better Defence Estate' strategy of 7 November 2016 announced the intended closure of Royal Marines Stonehouse by 2023 and outlined potential options for relocation of the Units currently located there (3 Commando Brigade Royal Marines HQ, Commander Amphibious Task Group HQ and 30 Commando (Information Exploitation Group) Royal Marines). Their future location remains subject to an assessment study that will report in the next 12 to 18 months and will inform more precisely the move dates and locations.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2017-01-31T16:03:51.197Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677996/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677996/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677996/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2017-01-24","Stonehouse Barracks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the proposed location for the Royal Marines currently occupying RMB Stonehouse is; and when relocation is planned to take place.","false","Biography information for Sir Gary Streeter","South West Devon","Mr Gary Streeter","61356"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677997","Department for Education","false","2017-02-02","<p>Apprenticeships offer a real opportunity to re-enter the labour market and those already in work the opportunity to progress further.</p><p>We provide a range of support for people to access, complete and progress in an apprenticeship especially those who are disadvantaged or who have additional needs, such as ex-offenders. We also offer a traineeship programme to help those that are further from being ready for an apprenticeship to prepare.</p><p>Additional support is also provided through the Department for Work and Pensions and the range of excellent organisations that work with ex-offenders.</p><p>In its White Paper, Prison Safety and Reform, published on 3 November the Ministry of Justice, set out its plans to develop a Prisoner Apprenticeship Pathway for prisoners which lead to an apprenticeship on release.</p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-02-02T14:43:01.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677997/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677997/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677997/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 56579, on apprenticeships, for what reason her Department has no plans to offer ex-offenders extra support.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61380"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677998","Department for Education","false","2017-01-27","<p>I refer the honourable member to my response to question 58497, which I have re-stated below.</p><p>The Department does not record, centrally, information on the costs of school closures.</p><p>The Department has not made an assessment of the number of schools that have closed and opened in the West Midlands, as compared with other regions; but the majority of academies that have closed since 2010 were merged with other schools rather than closed outright, which indicates this is likely to be for local organisational reasons.</p><p>Where a school closure is proposed, a number of factors must be considered and balanced against each other before a decision can be made, including the financial implications. The department does not consider it would be useful to collate information on the cost of school closure across the piece as it is important to consider this in the context of an individual case and in a way that provides value for money to the taxpayer.</p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-01-27T14:56:01.813Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677998/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677998/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677998/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Schools: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2016 to Question 57746, on schools closures, for what reason those costs are not collected centrally.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61379"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677999","Department for Education","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Index of Multiple Deprivation (IMD) is produced by the Department for Communities and Local Government (DCLG); it measures relative levels of deprivation in small areas or neighbourhoods, called Lower Super Output Areas (LSOAs). The 27 per cent most deprived areas as referred to in the question are the most deprived 27% of LSOAs (LSOAs ranking between 1-8867 on the IMD constitute the 27% most deprived).</p><p>Information and data on the Indices of Deprivation can be found at: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-indices-of-deprivation-2015" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/english-indices-of-deprivation-2015</a></p><p> </p><p> </p>","Harlow","Robert Halfon",,"2017-01-31T16:19:53.227Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677999/answer","Biography information for Robert Halfon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677999/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/677999/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Disadvantaged","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 16 December 2016 to Question 56579, what the 27 per cent most deprived areas are in order of deprivation.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61390"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678000","Department for Education","false","2017-01-27","<p>The estimated costs of the closure form only one element of the decision, which will take into consideration both the risks involved and dependencies required to deliver each of the options, and the best and most sustainable strategy for delivering good or outstanding school places for every child in the local area. The listening period for the proposed closure of Baverstock Academy ends on 7 February. This provides the opportunity for the community and stakeholders to make their representation to the Secretary of State before she makes a final decision. The priority for the Secretary of State in making a decision about the future of Baverstock Academy will be to deliver the best educational outcomes for local children.</p>","Crewe and Nantwich","Edward Timpson",,"2017-01-27T14:45:54.21Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678000/answer","Biography information for Edward Timpson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678000/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678000/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Baverstock Academy: Closures","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, pursuant to the Answer of 19 December 2016 to Question 57842, when she plans to publish the estimated cost of closing Baverstock Academy.","false","Biography information for Steve McCabe","Birmingham, Selly Oak","Steve McCabe","61381"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678001","Department for Education","false","2017-02-07","<p>For the current financial year 2016 to 2017, the pre-16 funding for secondary pupils is published here:<br><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017" target="_blank"><em>https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/schools-block-funding-allocations-2016-to-2017</em></a><em> <br> <br> </em></p><p>Schools selective status can be viewed here:<br><a href="http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml" target="_blank"><em>http://www.education.gov.uk/edubase/home.xhtml</em></a></p>","Bognor Regis and Littlehampton","Nick Gibb",,"2017-02-07T17:40:19.863Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678001/answer","Biography information for Nick Gibb","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678001/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678001/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Pupils: Per Capita Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how much her Department spends on each secondary school pupil in England and Wales; and how much is spent on places in (a) grammar and (b) non-selective school.","false","Biography information for Gareth Johnson","Dartford","Gareth Johnson","61440"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678002","Department for Education","false","2017-01-31","<p>The Civil Service Commissioners’ recruitment principles do not include selection exemptions.</p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2017-01-31T17:32:21.88Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678002/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678002/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/678002/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2017-01-24","Department for Education: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, how many times the selection exemptions of the Civil Service Commissioner's recruitment principles were used by her Department in each year since 2010; and at what grades each such appointment was made.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","61420"
